esham, Gloucestershire, England":"Tresham, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pembridge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Pembridge (Herefs), which is recorded as  <i>Penebrug(g)e</i> from the 11th to 14th centuries. The place-name derives from an Old English personal name * <i>Pena</i> + Old English  <i>brycg</i> ‘bridge’. In some cases the surname may be from Pen Bridge in Shipley (Sussex), which derives from an uncertain first element + Old English  <i>brycg</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Pember","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of <b>Pamber</b>, a habitational name from a place in Hampshire named Pamber, from Old English <i>penn</i> ‘fold, enclosure’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":9,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":22,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":31,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":76,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Pembridge was born in 1306, in Herefordshire, England, his father, William de Pembridge, was 31 and his mother, Margery de Burley, was 26. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret de Sarnesfield."},"et":{"1306–":"1306–Surnud","1306–Male":"1306–Surnud","1316–Female":"1316–Surnud","1332–1400":"1332–1400","1275–1300":"1275–1300","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1275":"1275","1382":"1382","1280":"1280","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1400":"1400","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1299":"1299","1453":"1453","1306":"1306","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Evesham, Gloucestershire, England":"Tresham, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"1306–":"1306–Kuollut","1306–Male":"1306–Kuollut","1316–Female":"1316–Kuollut","1332–1400":"1332–1400","1275–1300":"1275–1300","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1275":"1275","1382":"1382","1280":"1280","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1400":"1400","1300":"1300","1332":"13